### Recursion in Go

A recursive function calls itself.

### Factorial Example

```go
func factorial(n int) int {
    if n <= 1 {
        return 1
    }
    return n * factorial(n-1)
}

func main() {
    fmt.Println(factorial(5)) // 120
}
```

### Fibonacci Example

```go
func fibonacci(n int) int {
    if n <= 1 {
        return n
    }
    return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2)
}
```

### Tail Recursion

Go does not optimize tail recursion, but you can manually convert:

```go
// Tail recursive style
func factorialTail(n, acc int) int {
    if n <= 1 {
        return acc
    }
    return factorialTail(n-1, n*acc)
}

func factorial(n int) int {
    return factorialTail(n, 1)
}
```

### Recursion with Slice

```go
func sum(nums []int) int {
    if len(nums) == 0 {
        return 0
    }
    return nums[0] + sum(nums[1:])
}
```

### Tree Traversal

```go
type TreeNode struct {
    Value int
    Left  *TreeNode
    Right *TreeNode
}

func inOrder(node *TreeNode) {
    if node == nil {
        return
    }
    inOrder(node.Left)
    fmt.Println(node.Value)
    inOrder(node.Right)
}
```

### Stack Safety

Recursion depth is limited by the call stack. Go's goroutines start with small stacks (2KB) that grow as needed, but very deep recursion can still cause stack overflow:

```go
func deep(n int) int {
    if n == 0 {
        return 0
    }
    return 1 + deep(n-1)
}
// Safe up to ~100000 in Go
```

> **Key Point:** Go supports recursion but does not optimize tail calls. For very deep recursion, consider iterative approaches or use goroutines.

